2. WPI includes the prices of services.
Which is/are correct?', '2 only', '1 only', 'Both 1 and 2', 'Neither 1 nor 2', 'B', 'Core inflation strips out volatile food and fuel, while the WPI covers only goods, not services.', 2),
  ('upsc-economy-inflation-and-monetary-policy-q04', 'upsc-economy-inflation-and-monetary-policy', 'The repo rate is the rate at which:', 'Banks lend to the public', 'RBI borrows from banks', 'RBI lends to commercial banks', 'Banks lend to one another', 'C', 'Repo is the rate at which the RBI lends short-term funds to commercial banks against securities.', 3),
  ('upsc-economy-inflation-and-monetary-policy-q05', 'upsc-economy-inflation-and-monetary-policy', 'A situation of high inflation combined with stagnant growth and high unemployment is called:', 'Stagflation', 'Disinflation', 'Deflation', 'Reflation', 'A', 'Stagflation pairs rising prices with economic stagnation and high joblessness.', 4),
  ('upsc-economy-inflation-and-monetary-policy-q06', 'upsc-economy-inflation-and-monetary-policy', 'To control high inflation, the RBI would typically:', 'Reduce the repo rate', 'Raise the repo rate', 'Lower the CRR', 'Conduct OMO purchases', 'B', 'Raising the repo rate makes credit costlier, curbing demand and cooling inflation.', 5),
  ('upsc-economy-inflation-and-monetary-policy-q07', 'upsc-economy-inflation-and-monetary-policy', 'The headline Consumer Price Index in India is released by:', 'The Reserve Bank of India', 'The SEBI', 'The Office of the Economic Adviser', 'The NSO under MoSPI', 'D', 'The National Statistical Office under MoSPI compiles and releases the CPI.', 6),
  ('upsc-economy-inflation-and-monetary-policy-q08', 'upsc-economy-inflation-and-monetary-policy', '''Too much money chasing too few goods'' best describes which type of inflation?', 'Cost-push inflation', 'Demand-pull inflation', 'Structural inflation', 'Imported inflation', 'B', 'Demand-pull inflation arises when aggregate demand outstrips the available supply of goods.', 7),
  ('upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes-q01', 'upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes', 'Ayushman Bharat (PM-JAY) provides annual health cover of what amount per family?', '₹5 lakh', '₹3 lakh', '₹2 lakh', '₹10 lakh', 'A', 'PM-JAY gives a health cover of ₹5 lakh per family per year for secondary and tertiary care.', 0),
  ('upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes-q02', 'upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes', 'The ''JAM'' trinity used for Direct Benefit Transfer stands for:', 'Jan Dhan, Awas, MGNREGA', 'Jobs, Agriculture, Manufacturing', 'Jan Dhan, Aadhaar, Mobile', 'Justice, Aadhaar, Money', 'C', 'JAM links Jan Dhan accounts, Aadhaar identity and Mobile numbers to deliver subsidies directly.', 1),
  ('upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes-q03', 'upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes', 'PM-KISAN provides income support of how much per year to eligible farmer families?', '₹4,000', '₹12,000', '₹8,000', '₹6,000', 'D', 'PM-KISAN transfers ₹6,000 a year in three equal instalments of ₹2,000.', 2),
  ('upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes-q04', 'upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes', 'The Ujjwala Yojana is associated with the distribution of:', 'Solar panels', 'Free LPG connections', 'Bank accounts', 'Free housing', 'B', 'PM Ujjwala Yojana provides free LPG connections to women from below-poverty-line households.', 3),
  ('upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes-q05', 'upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes', 'MGNREGA guarantees how many days of wage employment per rural household per year?', '100 days', '50 days', '150 days', '200 days', 'A', 'The Act guarantees 100 days of unskilled manual wage employment to each rural household.', 4),
  ('upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes-q06', 'upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes', 'Consider the following statements:
1. PM Jan Dhan Yojana provides RuPay debit cards.
2. The Saubhagya scheme aims at universal household electrification.
Which is/are correct?', '1 only', '2 only', 'Both 1 and 2', 'Neither 1 nor 2', 'C', 'Jan Dhan accounts come with RuPay cards, while Saubhagya targets electricity for all households.', 5),
  ('upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes-q07', 'upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes', 'The Production-Linked Incentive (PLI) scheme is designed primarily to boost:', 'Agricultural exports', 'Tourism', 'Rural employment', 'Domestic manufacturing', 'D', 'PLI offers incentives on incremental sales to expand domestic manufacturing under Make in India.', 6),
  ('upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes-q08', 'upsc-current-affairs-government-schemes', 'The Swachh Bharat Mission is chiefly aimed at achieving:', 'Universal banking', 'An open-defecation-free India', 'Free education', 'Affordable housing', 'B', 'The mission focuses on sanitation and making India open-defecation-free through toilet construction.', 7),
  ('jee-physics-kinematics-1d-q01', 'jee-physics-kinematics-1d', 'A body starts from rest and accelerates at 2 m/s². How far does it travel in 5 s?', '10 m', '20 m', '50 m', '25 m', 'D', 's = ut + ½at² = 0 + ½(2)(25) = 25 m.', 0),
  ('jee-physics-kinematics-1d-q02', 'jee-physics-kinematics-1d', 'A stone is dropped from rest. Its velocity after 3 s (g = 10 m/s²) is:', '10 m/s', '30 m/s', '20 m/s', '45 m/s', 'B', 'v = u + gt = 0 + 10 × 3 = 30 m/s.', 1),
  ('jee-physics-kinematics-1d-q03', 'jee-physics-kinematics-1d', 'The area under a velocity–time graph represents:', 'Acceleration', 'Jerk', 'Displacement', 'Average speed', 'C', 'Integrating velocity over time gives displacement, which is the area under the v–t curve.', 2),
  ('jee-physics-kinematics-1d-q04', 'jee-physics-kinematics-1d', 'A car moving at 20 m/s decelerates uniformly and stops in 100 m. The deceleration is:', '1 m/s²', '10 m/s²', '4 m/s²', '2 m/s²', 'D', 'Using v² = u² + 2as: 0 = 400 + 2a(100), so a = −2 m/s².', 3),
  ('jee-physics-kinematics-1d-q05', 'jee-physics-kinematics-1d', 'The distance covered in the n-th second by a body from rest with acceleration a is:', '(a/2)(2n − 1)', 'an', '½an²', 'a(n − 1)', 'A', 's_nth = u + (a/2)(2n − 1); with u = 0 it reduces to (a/2)(2n − 1).', 4),
  ('jee-physics-kinematics-1d-q06', 'jee-physics-kinematics-1d', 'A ball thrown vertically up with 20 m/s reaches a maximum height of (g = 10 m/s²):', '20 m', '10 m', '30 m', '40 m', 'A', 'At the top v = 0, so h = u²/2g = 400/20 = 20 m.', 5),
  ('jee-physics-kinematics-1d-q07', 'jee-physics-kinematics-1d', 'If velocity is negative and acceleration is positive, the body is:', 'Speeding up', 'Slowing down', 'At rest', 'Moving at constant speed', 'B', 'Opposite signs of v and a mean the speed (magnitude) is decreasing.', 6),
  ('jee-physics-kinematics-1d-q08', 'jee-physics-kinematics-1d', 'Two balls are dropped 1 s apart from the same height. As they fall, the gap between them:', 'Increases', 'Decreases', 'Stays constant', 'First increases then decreases', 'A', 'The earlier ball is always faster, so the separation grows with time.', 7),
  ('jee-physics-rotational-motion-q01', 'jee-physics-rotational-motion', 'The moment of inertia of a solid sphere about a diameter is:', 'MR²', '(2/3)MR²', '(1/2)MR²', '(2/5)MR²', 'D', 'A uniform solid sphere has I = (2/5)MR² about any diameter.', 0),
  ('jee-physics-rotational-motion-q02', 'jee-physics-rotational-motion', 'The rotational analogue of force is:', 'Torque', 'Momentum', 'Impulse', 'Power', 'A', 'Torque τ = Iα plays the role of force F = ma in rotation.', 1),
  ('jee-physics-rotational-motion-q03', 'jee-physics-rotational-motion', 'A skater pulls in her arms while spinning. Her angular velocity:', 'Increases', 'Decreases', 'Stays the same', 'Becomes zero', 'A', 'With torque zero, L = Iω is conserved; reducing I increases ω.', 2),
  ('jee-physics-rotational-motion-q04', 'jee-physics-rotational-motion', 'Which body reaches the bottom of an incline first while rolling without slipping?', 'Hollow cylinder', 'Solid sphere', 'Ring', 'Hollow sphere', 'B', 'The solid sphere has the smallest I/MR² (2/5), giving the largest acceleration.', 3),
  ('jee-physics-rotational-motion-q05', 'jee-physics-rotational-motion', 'The parallel axis theorem states I = :', 'I_cm + Md²', 'I_cm − Md²', 'I_cm + ½Md²', '2I_cm + Md²', 'A', 'I about a parallel axis equals the centre-of-mass value plus Md².', 4),
  ('jee-physics-rotational-motion-q06', 'jee-physics-rotational-motion', 'For rolling without slipping, the velocity of the contact point with the ground is:', 'v', 'Zero', '2v', 'v/2', 'B', 'In pure rolling, the instantaneous velocity of the contact point is zero.', 5),
  ('jee-physics-rotational-motion-q07', 'jee-physics-rotational-motion', 'The rotational kinetic energy of a body is:', '½Iω', 'Iω²', '½Iω²', '½I²ω', 'C', 'Rotational KE = ½Iω², analogous to ½mv² for translation.', 6),
  ('jee-physics-rotational-motion-q08', 'jee-physics-rotational-motion', 'A disc of moment of inertia 2 kg·m² spins at 3 rad/s. Its angular momentum is:', '3 kg·m²/s', '6 kg·m²/s', '5 kg·m²/s', '9 kg·m²/s', 'B', 'L = Iω = 2 × 3 = 6 kg·m²/s.', 7),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding-q01', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding', 'The shape of a molecule with sp³ hybridisation and no lone pairs is:', 'Linear', 'Trigonal planar', 'Tetrahedral', 'Octahedral', 'C', 'Four equivalent sp³ orbitals point to the corners of a tetrahedron (109.5°).', 0),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding-q02', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding', 'The bond angle in a water molecule is approximately:', '90°', '109.5°', '104.5°', '120°', 'C', 'Two lone pairs on the sp³ oxygen compress the H–O–H angle to about 104.5°.', 1),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding-q03', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding', 'Which molecule has a zero net dipole moment despite polar bonds?', 'H₂O', 'NH₃', 'HCl', 'CO₂', 'D', 'CO₂ is linear and symmetric, so the two bond dipoles cancel exactly.', 2),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding-q04', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding', 'The bond order of the oxygen molecule (O₂) from MO theory is:', '1', '2', '1.5', '3', 'B', 'O₂ has a bond order of 2 and two unpaired electrons, making it paramagnetic.', 3),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding-q05', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding', 'According to Fajans'' rules, covalent character increases with:', 'Large cation, small anion', 'Large anion, large cation', 'Low cation charge', 'Small cation, large anion', 'D', 'A small, highly charged cation polarises a large anion, increasing covalent character.', 4),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding-q06', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding', 'The hybridisation of carbon in ethyne (C₂H₂) is:', 'sp³d', 'sp²', 'sp³', 'sp', 'D', 'The triple-bonded carbons in ethyne are sp hybridised, giving a linear molecule.', 5),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding-q07', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding', 'The unusually high boiling point of water is mainly due to:', 'Ionic bonding', 'Van der Waals forces', 'Hydrogen bonding', 'Metallic bonding', 'C', 'Extensive hydrogen bonding between water molecules requires extra energy to break.', 6),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding-q08', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-bonding', 'In the ammonium ion (NH₄⁺), the fourth N–H bond is a:', 'Ionic bond', 'Coordinate bond', 'Hydrogen bond', 'Metallic bond', 'B', 'The lone pair on nitrogen forms a coordinate (dative) bond with the proton.', 7),
  ('jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations-q01', 'jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations', 'For the equation x² − 5x + 6 = 0, the sum of the roots is:', '5', '−5', '6', '−6', 'A', 'Sum of roots = −b/a = −(−5)/1 = 5 (roots are 2 and 3).', 0),
  ('jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations-q02', 'jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations', 'The discriminant of 2x² + 3x + 5 = 0 is:', '31', '49', '−31', '−49', 'C', 'D = b² − 4ac = 9 − 40 = −31, so the roots are complex.', 1),
  ('jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations-q03', 'jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations', 'If the roots of a quadratic are equal, the discriminant is:', 'Positive', 'Negative', 'Irrational', 'Zero', 'D', 'Equal real roots occur exactly when D = b² − 4ac = 0.', 2),
  ('jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations-q04', 'jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations', 'The quadratic equation whose roots are 3 and −2 is:', 'x² − 5x + 6 = 0', 'x² + x − 6 = 0', 'x² − x − 6 = 0', 'x² + 5x + 6 = 0', 'C', 'Sum = 1, product = −6, so x² − (1)x + (−6) = x² − x − 6 = 0.', 3),
  ('jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations-q05', 'jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations', 'For ax² + bx + c > 0 to hold for all real x, we require:', 'a > 0 and D > 0', 'a < 0 and D > 0', 'a < 0 and D < 0', 'a > 0 and D < 0', 'D', 'An upward parabola (a > 0) that never touches the x-axis (D < 0) is always positive.', 4),
  ('jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations-q06', 'jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations', 'If α and β are roots of x² − 6x + 8 = 0, then α² + β² equals:', '16', '20', '36', '52', 'B', 'α² + β² = (α + β)² − 2αβ = 36 − 16 = 20.', 5),
  ('jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations-q07', 'jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations', 'The vertex of the parabola y = x² − 4x + 7 lies at x =:', '2', '1', '4', '−2', 'A', 'The vertex is at x = −b/(2a) = 4/2 = 2.', 6),
  ('jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations-q08', 'jee-mathematics-quadratic-equations', 'The product of the roots of 3x² − 12x + 9 = 0 is:', '1', '4', '3', '9', 'C', 'Product = c/a = 9/3 = 3.', 7),
  ('neet-biology-cell-structure-function-q01', 'neet-biology-cell-structure-function', 'Which organelle is known as the ''powerhouse of the cell''?', 'Ribosome', 'Mitochondrion', 'Golgi apparatus', 'Lysosome', 'B', 'Mitochondria generate most cellular ATP through aerobic respiration.', 0),
  ('neet-biology-cell-structure-function-q02', 'neet-biology-cell-structure-function', 'Ribosomes found in the cytoplasm of eukaryotic cells are of the type:', '80S', '70S', '50S', '30S', 'A', 'Eukaryotic cytoplasmic ribosomes are 80S; the 70S type occurs in mitochondria and chloroplasts.', 1),
  ('neet-biology-cell-structure-function-q03', 'neet-biology-cell-structure-function', 'Which structure is present in plant cells but absent in animal cells?', 'Mitochondrion', 'Nucleus', 'Cellulose cell wall', 'Ribosome', 'C', 'A rigid cellulose cell wall surrounds plant cells but is absent in animal cells.', 2),
  ('neet-biology-cell-structure-function-q04', 'neet-biology-cell-structure-function', 'Lysosomes are often called the ''suicide bags'' because they contain:', 'Photosynthetic pigments', 'DNA', 'Hydrolytic enzymes', 'Ribosomes', 'C', 'Lysosomes are packed with hydrolytic enzymes that can digest the cell''s own components.', 3),
  ('neet-biology-cell-structure-function-q05', 'neet-biology-cell-structure-function', 'The fluid-mosaic model of the plasma membrane was proposed by:', 'Schleiden and Schwann', 'Robert Hooke', 'Watson and Crick', 'Singer and Nicolson', 'D', 'Singer and Nicolson (1972) described the membrane as a lipid bilayer with mobile proteins.', 4),
  ('neet-biology-cell-structure-function-q06', 'neet-biology-cell-structure-function', 'Which feature distinguishes a prokaryotic from a eukaryotic cell?', 'Absence of a membrane-bound nucleus', 'Presence of a plasma membrane', 'Presence of ribosomes', 'Presence of cytoplasm', 'A', 'Prokaryotes lack a true membrane-bound nucleus; their DNA lies in a nucleoid region.', 5),
  ('neet-biology-cell-structure-function-q07', 'neet-biology-cell-structure-function', 'The nucleolus is the site of synthesis of:', 'DNA', 'Lipids', 'rRNA', 'ATP', 'C', 'The nucleolus is the centre of ribosomal RNA synthesis and ribosome assembly.', 6),
  ('neet-biology-cell-structure-function-q08', 'neet-biology-cell-structure-function', '''Omnis cellula e cellula'', meaning new cells arise from existing cells, was stated by:', 'Robert Hooke', 'Theodor Schwann', 'Rudolf Virchow', 'Anton van Leeuwenhoek', 'C', 'Virchow extended the cell theory with the principle that every cell comes from a pre-existing cell.', 7),
  ('neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion-q01', 'neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion', 'Salivary amylase (ptyalin) acts on:', 'Starch', 'Fats', 'Proteins', 'Nucleic acids', 'A', 'Ptyalin begins starch digestion in the mouth, converting it to maltose.', 0),
  ('neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion-q02', 'neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion', 'Pepsin is secreted in an inactive form called:', 'Trypsinogen', 'Prorennin', 'Pepsinogen', 'Chymotrypsinogen', 'C', 'Inactive pepsinogen is activated to pepsin by the HCl of gastric juice.', 1),
  ('neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion-q03', 'neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion', 'Bile, secreted by the liver, helps digestion by:', 'Breaking proteins', 'Emulsifying fats', 'Hydrolysing starch', 'Absorbing water', 'B', 'Bile salts emulsify large fat globules into smaller droplets for lipase to act on.', 2),
  ('neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion-q04', 'neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion', 'Most absorption of digested food occurs in the:', 'Stomach', 'Oesophagus', 'Large intestine', 'Small intestine', 'D', 'Villi and microvilli of the small intestine provide a huge surface for absorption.', 3),
  ('neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion-q05', 'neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion', 'The adult human dental formula 2123/2123 corresponds to how many teeth?', '20', '28', '32', '36', 'C', 'Each half-jaw has 2 incisors, 1 canine, 2 premolars, 3 molars; total 32 teeth.', 4),
  ('neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion-q06', 'neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion', 'The largest gland in the human body is the:', 'Pancreas', 'Liver', 'Salivary gland', 'Thyroid', 'B', 'The liver is the largest gland; it produces bile and stores glycogen.', 5),
  ('neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion-q07', 'neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion', 'Intrinsic factor secreted by the stomach is essential for the absorption of:', 'Vitamin C', 'Calcium', 'Iron', 'Vitamin B₁₂', 'D', 'Intrinsic factor binds vitamin B₁₂, enabling its absorption in the ileum.', 6),
  ('neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion-q08', 'neet-biology-human-physiology-digestion', 'Which enzyme from the pancreas digests fats?', 'Lipase', 'Amylase', 'Trypsin', 'Pepsin', 'A', 'Pancreatic lipase breaks fats into fatty acids and glycerol.', 7),
  ('neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics-q01', 'neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics', 'The correct order of stability of carbocations is:', 'Methyl > 1° > 2° > 3°', '2° > 3° > 1° > methyl', '1° > 2° > 3° > methyl', '3° > 2° > 1° > methyl', 'D', 'Hyperconjugation and the +I effect make tertiary carbocations the most stable.', 0),
  ('neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics-q02', 'neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics', 'An electrophile is a species that is:', 'Electron-rich', 'A free radical', 'Always negatively charged', 'Electron-deficient', 'D', 'Electrophiles are electron-poor and accept an electron pair from a nucleophile.', 1),
  ('neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics-q03', 'neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics', 'Which group shows a +M (electron-donating resonance) effect?', '−NO₂', '−C≡N', '−NH₂', '−COOH', 'C', 'The lone pair on −NH₂ is donated into the ring, a +M effect.', 2),
  ('neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics-q04', 'neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics', 'The hybridisation of the positively charged carbon in a carbocation is:', 'sp²', 'sp', 'sp³', 'sp³d', 'A', 'A carbocation carbon is sp² hybridised with an empty p-orbital, giving planar geometry.', 3),
  ('neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics-q05', 'neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics', 'Which of the following is the most acidic?', 'Ethanol', 'Acetic acid', 'Phenol', 'Water', 'B', 'Carboxylic acids are more acidic than phenols, alcohols and water due to resonance-stabilised anions.', 4),
  ('neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics-q06', 'neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics', 'Hyperconjugation involves the delocalisation of electrons from:', 'A σ (C–H) bond', 'A π bond only', 'A lone pair', 'A d orbital', 'A', 'Hyperconjugation delocalises σ(C–H) bond electrons into an adjacent empty or π orbital.', 5),
  ('neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics-q07', 'neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics', 'A chiral carbon atom must be bonded to:', 'Four different groups', 'Two identical groups', 'A double bond', 'A hydrogen only', 'A', 'Optical activity requires a carbon attached to four different groups (a stereocentre).', 6),
  ('neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics-q08', 'neet-chemistry-organic-chemistry-basics', 'Electron-withdrawing groups attached to an acid generally:', 'Decrease acidity', 'Increase acidity', 'Have no effect', 'Make it basic', 'B', 'They stabilise the conjugate base by dispersing negative charge, increasing acidity.', 7),
  ('neet-physics-ray-optics-q01', 'neet-physics-ray-optics', 'The focal length of a spherical mirror is related to its radius of curvature by:', 'f = R', 'f = 2R', 'f = R/4', 'f = R/2', 'D', 'For a spherical mirror the focal length is half the radius of curvature, f = R/2.', 0),
  ('neet-physics-ray-optics-q02', 'neet-physics-ray-optics', 'Total internal reflection occurs when light travels from a:', 'Rarer to a denser medium', 'Denser to a rarer medium at normal incidence', 'Medium to vacuum at any angle', 'Denser to a rarer medium beyond the critical angle', 'D', 'TIR needs a denser-to-rarer transition with the incidence angle exceeding the critical angle.', 1),
  ('neet-physics-ray-optics-q03', 'neet-physics-ray-optics', 'The power of a lens of focal length 50 cm is:', '0.5 D', '5 D', '2 D', '50 D', 'C', 'P = 1/f(m) = 1/0.5 = 2 dioptres.', 2),
  ('neet-physics-ray-optics-q04', 'neet-physics-ray-optics', 'A convex lens always forms which type of image of a distant object?', 'Virtual and erect', 'Real and erect', 'Virtual and inverted', 'Real and inverted', 'D', 'A converging lens forms a real, inverted image of a distant real object on the far side.', 3),
  ('neet-physics-ray-optics-q05', 'neet-physics-ray-optics', 'Snell''s law relates the angles of incidence and refraction through:', 'n₁ cos i = n₂ cos r', 'n₁ sin i = n₂ sin r', 'n₁ tan i = n₂ tan r', 'n₁ i = n₂ r', 'B', 'Snell''s law states n₁ sin i = n₂ sin r at a refracting boundary.', 4),
  ('neet-physics-ray-optics-q06', 'neet-physics-ray-optics', 'Two thin lenses of power +3 D and +2 D placed in contact have a combined power of:', '5 D', '1 D', '6 D', '1.2 D', 'A', 'Powers add for lenses in contact: P = 3 + 2 = 5 D.', 5),
  ('neet-physics-ray-optics-q07', 'neet-physics-ray-optics', 'A prism produces a spectrum of white light because the refractive index:', 'Is constant for all colours', 'Depends on wavelength', 'Depends on the prism mass', 'Is zero for violet light', 'B', 'Refractive index varies with wavelength, so violet bends most and red least (dispersion).', 6),
  ('neet-physics-ray-optics-q08', 'neet-physics-ray-optics', 'A convex mirror always forms an image that is:', 'Real and inverted', 'Virtual, erect and diminished', 'Real and magnified', 'Virtual and magnified', 'B', 'A convex (diverging) mirror always gives a virtual, erect, diminished image, useful as a rear-view mirror.', 7),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss-q01', 'ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss', 'A price is increased by 20% and then decreased by 20%. The net change is:', '0%', '+4%', '−4%', '−2%', 'C', 'Net% = 20 − 20 − (400/100) = −4%, a net decrease.', 0),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss-q02', 'ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss', 'An article bought for ₹400 is sold for ₹500. The profit percentage is:', '25%', '20%', '30%', '40%', 'A', 'Profit% = (100/400) × 100 = 25%.', 1),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss-q03', 'ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss', 'What is 35% of 240?', '84', '80', '74', '96', 'A', '35% of 240 = 0.35 × 240 = 84.', 2),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss-q04', 'ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss', 'Two items are sold at the same price, one at 10% profit and one at 10% loss. The overall result is:', 'No profit, no loss', '1% profit', '1% loss', '2% loss', 'C', 'Selling at equal SP with ±x% gives a loss of (x/10)² = (10/10)² = 1%.', 3),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss-q05', 'ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss', 'A shopkeeper marks an item at ₹800 and gives a 15% discount. The selling price is:', '₹640', '₹700', '₹680', '₹720', 'C', 'SP = 800 × (85/100) = ₹680.', 4),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss-q06', 'ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss', 'If 60 is what percent of 150?', '40%', '25%', '45%', '50%', 'A', '(60/150) × 100 = 40%.', 5),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss-q07', 'ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss', 'By selling a pen for ₹54, a man loses 10%. The cost price was:', '₹58', '₹60', '₹62', '₹64', 'B', 'CP = 54 / 0.90 = ₹60.', 6),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss-q08', 'ssc-cgl-quant-percentages-profit-loss', 'A number increased by 25% becomes 250. The original number is:', '180', '200', '210', '225', 'B', 'Original = 250 / 1.25 = 200.', 7),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance-q01', 'ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance', 'A car covers 180 km in 3 hours. Its speed is:', '50 km/h', '70 km/h', '60 km/h', '90 km/h', 'C', 'Speed = 180/3 = 60 km/h.', 0),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance-q02', 'ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance', 'Convert 72 km/h into m/s:', '20 m/s', '18 m/s', '15 m/s', '25 m/s', 'A', '72 × 5/18 = 20 m/s.', 1),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance-q03', 'ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance', 'A man covers equal distances at 30 km/h and 60 km/h. His average speed is:', '48 km/h', '45 km/h', '40 km/h', '50 km/h', 'C', 'Average = 2uv/(u+v) = 2(30)(60)/90 = 40 km/h.', 2),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance-q04', 'ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance', 'Two trains move towards each other at 40 km/h and 50 km/h. Their relative speed is:', '90 km/h', '45 km/h', '10 km/h', '100 km/h', 'A', 'For opposite directions, relative speed is the sum: 40 + 50 = 90 km/h.', 3),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance-q05', 'ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance', 'A 150 m long train running at 20 m/s crosses a pole in:', '5 s', '10 s', '7.5 s', '12 s', 'C', 'Time = length/speed = 150/20 = 7.5 s.', 4),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance-q06', 'ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance', 'A boat goes 12 km/h downstream and 8 km/h upstream. The speed of the stream is:', '2 km/h', '4 km/h', '6 km/h', '10 km/h', 'A', 'Stream speed = (down − up)/2 = (12 − 8)/2 = 2 km/h.', 5),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance-q07', 'ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance', 'If a journey of 240 km takes 4 hours, how long will 360 km take at the same speed?', '6 hours', '5 hours', '7 hours', '8 hours', 'A', 'Speed = 60 km/h, so 360/60 = 6 hours.', 6),
  ('ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance-q08', 'ssc-cgl-quant-time-speed-distance', 'A 120 m train at 15 m/s crosses a 180 m platform in:', '15 s', '18 s', '24 s', '20 s', 'D', 'Time = (120 + 180)/15 = 300/15 = 20 s.', 7),
  ('ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series-q01', 'ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series', 'If CAT is coded as DBU, then DOG is coded as:', 'FPH', 'EPF', 'EPH', 'CPH', 'C', 'Each letter shifts forward by one: D→E, O→P, G→H.', 0),
  ('ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series-q02', 'ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series', 'Find the next term: 2, 6, 12, 20, 30, ?', '42', '40', '44', '36', 'A', 'Differences are 4, 6, 8, 10, then 12; 30 + 12 = 42.', 1),
  ('ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series-q03', 'ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series', 'What is the position of the letter T in the English alphabet?', '20', '19', '18', '21', 'A', 'Using EJOTY, T is the 20th letter.', 2),
  ('ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series-q04', 'ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series', 'Complete the series: 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, ?', '11', '13', '12', '15', 'B', 'Fibonacci: each term is the sum of the two before it; 5 + 8 = 13.', 3),
  ('ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series-q05', 'ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series', 'In a code, A is written as Z, B as Y, C as X. How is D written?', 'U', 'V', 'X', 'W', 'D', 'Opposite coding: each letter maps to 27 − n, so D (4) → 23 → W.', 4),
  ('ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series-q06', 'ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series', 'Find the missing term: 3, 9, 27, 81, ?', '162', '210', '243', '324', 'C', 'Each term is multiplied by 3; 81 × 3 = 243.', 5),
  ('ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series-q07', 'ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series', 'If 5 is coded as 36 and 6 as 49, then 7 is coded as:', '56', '63', '81', '64', 'D', 'The code is (n + 1)²; (7 + 1)² = 64.', 6),
  ('ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series-q08', 'ssc-cgl-reasoning-coding-decoding-series', 'Find the odd one in the number series: 4, 9, 16, 25, 35, 49', '16', '25', '35', '49', 'C', 'All are perfect squares except 35 (36 would fit the pattern).', 7),
  ('ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word-q01', 'ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word', 'The idiom ''to let the cat out of the bag'' means:', 'To buy a pet', 'To take a risk', 'To run away', 'To reveal a secret', 'D', 'It means to disclose a secret, usually by accident.', 0),
  ('ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word-q02', 'ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word', 'One word for ''a person who studies birds'' is:', 'Botanist', 'Ornithologist', 'Zoologist', 'Entomologist', 'B', 'Ornithology is the study of birds, so the practitioner is an ornithologist.', 1),
  ('ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word-q03', 'ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word', 'The idiom ''a blessing in disguise'' means:', 'A hidden danger', 'An obvious gift', 'A bad omen', 'A good thing that seemed bad at first', 'D', 'It refers to something that turns out beneficial despite seeming unfortunate initially.', 2),
  ('ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word-q04', 'ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word', 'One word for ''words inscribed on a tomb'' is:', 'Epithet', 'Epigram', 'Epilogue', 'Epitaph', 'D', 'An epitaph is the inscription on a gravestone or tomb.', 3),
  ('ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word-q05', 'ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word', '''Once in a blue moon'' means an event that happens:', 'Very often', 'Every month', 'At night only', 'Very rarely', 'D', 'The idiom denotes something happening extremely rarely.', 4),
  ('ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word-q06', 'ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word', 'One word for ''a person who hates mankind'' is:', 'Philanthropist', 'Egotist', 'Misogynist', 'Misanthrope', 'D', 'A misanthrope dislikes or distrusts humankind; a philanthropist loves it.', 5),
  ('ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word-q07', 'ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word', 'To ''burn the midnight oil'' means to:', 'Waste resources', 'Work late into the night', 'Start a fire', 'Sleep early', 'B', 'The idiom describes studying or working late into the night.', 6),
  ('ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word-q08', 'ssc-cgl-english-idioms-one-word', 'One word for ''a person who walks on a tightrope'' is:', 'Acrobat', 'Equestrian', 'Somnambulist', 'Funambulist', 'D', 'A funambulist is a tightrope walker; a somnambulist is a sleepwalker.', 7),
  ('ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts-q01', 'ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts', 'The Indian Constitution came into force on:', '15 August 1947', '26 January 1950', '26 November 1949', '2 October 1950', 'B', 'Though adopted on 26 November 1949, it came into force on 26 January 1950.', 0),
  ('ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts-q02', 'ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts', 'Who was the Chairman of the Drafting Committee of the Constitution?', 'Jawaharlal Nehru', 'Rajendra Prasad', 'Sardar Patel', 'B.R. Ambedkar', 'D', 'Dr. B.R. Ambedkar chaired the Drafting Committee of the Constituent Assembly.', 1),
  ('ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts-q03', 'ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts', 'The Fundamental Duties were added to the Constitution by which amendment?', '44th Amendment', '42nd Amendment', '52nd Amendment', '73rd Amendment', 'B', 'The 42nd Amendment (1976) added the Fundamental Duties under Article 51A.', 2),
  ('ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts-q04', 'ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts', 'Which Article of the Constitution deals with the office of the President?', 'Article 52', 'Article 63', 'Article 75', 'Article 76', 'A', 'Article 52 establishes the office of the President of India.', 3),
  ('ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts-q05', 'ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts', 'The Eighth Schedule of the Constitution deals with:', 'Anti-defection', 'Official languages', 'Union and State lists', 'Panchayats', 'B', 'The Eighth Schedule lists the recognised official languages, now 22 in number.', 4),
  ('ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts-q06', 'ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts', 'The concept of Directive Principles of State Policy was borrowed from:', 'The USA', 'Ireland', 'The UK', 'Canada', 'B', 'India adopted the Directive Principles from the Irish Constitution.', 5),
  ('ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts-q07', 'ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts', 'The Finance Commission is constituted under which Article and at what interval?', 'Article 324, every 6 years', 'Article 280, every 5 years', 'Article 148, annually', 'Article 280, every 10 years', 'B', 'Article 280 provides for a Finance Commission constituted every five years.', 6),
  ('ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts-q08', 'ssc-cgl-general-awareness-indian-polity-facts', 'The 42nd Amendment (1976) added which words to the Preamble?', 'Sovereign and Republic', 'Democratic and Justice', 'Socialist, Secular and Integrity', 'Liberty and Equality', 'C', 'The 42nd Amendment inserted ''Socialist'', ''Secular'' and ''Integrity'' into the Preamble.', 7),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra-q01', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra', 'A square matrix A is invertible if and only if:', 'det(A) = 0', 'det(A) ≠ 0', 'trace(A) = 0', 'A is symmetric', 'B', 'A matrix is non-singular (invertible) exactly when its determinant is non-zero.', 0),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra-q02', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra', 'The sum of the eigenvalues of a matrix equals its:', 'Determinant', 'Trace', 'Rank', 'Norm', 'B', 'The sum of eigenvalues equals the trace; their product equals the determinant.', 1),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra-q03', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra', 'If the eigenvalues of A are 2 and 3, the eigenvalues of A⁻¹ are:', '2 and 3', '−2 and −3', '1/2 and 1/3', '4 and 9', 'C', 'Eigenvalues of the inverse are the reciprocals of the original eigenvalues.', 2),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra-q04', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra', 'The eigenvalues of a triangular matrix are:', 'Its diagonal entries', 'Always zero', 'Its off-diagonal entries', 'Always complex', 'A', 'For a triangular matrix, the eigenvalues are simply the diagonal elements.', 3),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra-q05', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra', 'A real symmetric matrix always has:', 'Real eigenvalues', 'Complex eigenvalues', 'Zero determinant', 'Equal eigenvalues', 'A', 'Real symmetric matrices are guaranteed to have real eigenvalues.', 4),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra-q06', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra', 'For the system Ax = b to have a unique solution, the rank must satisfy:', 'rank(A) = rank(A|b) = n', 'rank(A) < n', 'rank(A) ≠ rank(A|b)', 'rank(A) = 0', 'A', 'A unique solution needs the coefficient and augmented ranks to equal the number of unknowns n.', 5),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra-q07', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra', 'The Cayley–Hamilton theorem states that every square matrix satisfies its own:', 'Trace equation', 'Determinant', 'Characteristic equation', 'Inverse', 'C', 'Every matrix satisfies its characteristic equation, enabling quick computation of inverses and powers.', 6),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra-q08', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-linear-algebra', 'If det(A) = 5 and det(B) = 2 for 3×3 matrices, then det(AB) is:', '7', '25', '10', '0', 'C', 'det(AB) = det(A)·det(B) = 5 × 2 = 10.', 7),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-probability-q01', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-probability', 'Two events A and B are independent when:', 'P(A ∩ B) = 0', 'P(A) = P(B)', 'P(A ∪ B) = 1', 'P(A ∩ B) = P(A)·P(B)', 'D', 'Independence means the joint probability equals the product of the individual probabilities.', 0),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-probability-q02', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-probability', 'The mean of a binomial distribution with parameters n and p is:', 'np(1−p)', 'np', 'p/n', 'n/p', 'B', 'The binomial mean is np; its variance is np(1−p).', 1),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-probability-q03', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-probability', 'For a Poisson distribution, the variance equals:', 'λ²', '1/λ', '√λ', 'λ', 'D', 'A Poisson distribution has mean and variance both equal to λ.', 2),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-probability-q04', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-probability', 'The expected value when rolling a single fair six-sided die is:', '3', '4', '3.5', '6', 'C', 'E(X) = (1+2+3+4+5+6)/6 = 21/6 = 3.5.', 3),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-probability-q05', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-probability', 'The variance of a random variable is given by:', 'E(X) − E(X²)', 'E(X²) + E(X)', '[E(X)]² − E(X²)', 'E(X²) − [E(X)]²', 'D', 'Var(X) = E(X²) − [E(X)]² by definition.', 4),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-probability-q06', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-probability', 'Two fair coins are tossed. The probability of getting exactly one head is:', '1/4', '1/3', '1/2', '3/4', 'C', 'Outcomes HT and TH out of four equally likely give 2/4 = 1/2.', 5),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-probability-q07', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-probability', 'Conditional probability P(A|B) is defined as:', 'P(A) · P(B)', 'P(A ∩ B) / P(B)', 'P(A ∪ B) / P(B)', 'P(B) / P(A)', 'B', 'P(A|B) = P(A ∩ B)/P(B), assuming P(B) > 0.', 6),
  ('gate-engineering-mathematics-probability-q08', 'gate-engineering-mathematics-probability', 'Adding a constant b to a random variable X changes its variance by:', 'No change', 'b²', 'b', '2b', 'A', 'Var(X + b) = Var(X); shifting by a constant does not affect variance.', 7),
  ('gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles-q01', 'gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles', 'If A : B = 2 : 3 and B : C = 4 : 5, then A : C is:', '2 : 5', '5 : 8', '8 : 15', '3 : 4', 'C', 'Scale to A : B : C = 8 : 12 : 15, so A : C = 8 : 15.', 0),
  ('gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles-q02', 'gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles', '₹1200 is divided between two people in the ratio 2 : 3. The larger share is:', '₹480', '₹600', '₹800', '₹720', 'D', 'The larger share = (3/5) × 1200 = ₹720.', 1),
  ('gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles-q03', 'gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles', 'The mean proportional between 4 and 16 is:', '8', '6', '10', '12', 'A', 'Mean proportional = √(4 × 16) = √64 = 8.', 2),
  ('gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles-q04', 'gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles', 'A does a job in 10 days and B in 15 days. Working together they finish in:', '5 days', '12 days', '8 days', '6 days', 'D', 'Combined rate = 1/10 + 1/15 = 1/6, so they finish in 6 days.', 3),
  ('gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles-q05', 'gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles', 'Pointing to a photo, a man says, ''She is my mother''s only daughter.'' The photo is of his:', 'Wife', 'Sister', 'Mother', 'Daughter', 'B', 'His mother''s only daughter is his sister.', 4),
  ('gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles-q06', 'gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles', 'A man walks 5 km north, then 3 km east, then 5 km south. How far is he from the start?', '2 km', '3 km', '5 km', '8 km', 'B', 'The north and south cancel, leaving 3 km east of the start.', 5),
  ('gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles-q07', 'gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles', 'In what ratio must rice at ₹30/kg be mixed with rice at ₹40/kg to get a mixture at ₹36/kg?', '3 : 2', '2 : 3', '4 : 6', '6 : 4', 'B', 'By alligation, ratio = (40−36) : (36−30) = 4 : 6 = 2 : 3.', 6),
  ('gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles-q08', 'gate-general-aptitude-ratio-logical-puzzles', 'If 3 men can build a wall in 8 days, how many days will 4 men take (same rate)?', '6 days', '4 days', '8 days', '10 days', 'A', 'Work is constant: 3 × 8 = 4 × d, so d = 24/4 = 6 days.', 7),
  ('gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees-q01', 'gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees', 'The average-case time complexity of search in a balanced binary search tree is:', 'O(1)', 'O(n)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n log n)', 'C', 'A balanced BST keeps height at log n, giving O(log n) search.', 0),
  ('gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees-q02', 'gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees', 'The maximum number of nodes in a binary tree of height h is:', '2^h − 1', '2^(h+1) − 1', '2^h', 'h²', 'B', 'A full binary tree of height h holds 2^(h+1) − 1 nodes.', 1),
  ('gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees-q03', 'gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees', 'Which traversal of a binary search tree visits nodes in sorted order?', 'Preorder', 'Level-order', 'Postorder', 'Inorder', 'D', 'Inorder traversal (L, root, R) of a BST yields keys in ascending order.', 2),
  ('gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees-q04', 'gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees', 'The average-case time to search in a hash table is:', 'O(1)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n)', 'O(n²)', 'A', 'With good hashing and few collisions, hash-table search is O(1) on average.', 3),
  ('gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees-q05', 'gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees', 'In a binary heap stored in an array, the children of node at index i are at:', 'i−1 and i+1', '2i and 2i+1 (0-indexed)', 'i/2 and 2i', '2i+1 and 2i+2 (0-indexed)', 'D', 'For a 0-indexed array heap, node i has children at 2i+1 and 2i+2.', 4),
  ('gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees-q06', 'gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees', 'Which notation describes the tight asymptotic bound of an algorithm?', 'Big-Θ', 'Big-Ω', 'Big-O', 'Little-o', 'A', 'Big-Θ gives a tight bound, sandwiching the function between O and Ω.', 5),
  ('gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees-q07', 'gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees', 'Searching an unsorted array of n elements has worst-case complexity:', 'O(1)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n)', 'O(n²)', 'C', 'A linear scan may inspect all n elements, giving O(n).', 6),
  ('gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees-q08', 'gate-core-cs-data-structures-complexity-trees', 'A binary search tree degrades to O(n) operations when it is:', 'Perfectly balanced', 'Empty', 'Complete', 'Completely skewed', 'D', 'A fully skewed BST behaves like a linked list, making operations O(n).', 7)
on conflict (id) do update set topic_id = excluded.topic_id, text = excluded.text, option_a = excluded.option_a, option_b = excluded.option_b, option_c = excluded.option_c, option_d = excluded.option_d, correct_option = excluded.correct_option, explanation = excluded.explanation, order_index = excluded.order_index;


commit;

